{
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "HyperText Markup Language as the standard for structuring web content. Defines the skeleton of web pages using tags and elements.",
      "title": "What is HTML?"
    },
    {
      "description": "Basic layout of an HTML file including the doctype declaration. Root html element and its child head and body elements.",
      "title": "HTML Document Structure"
    },
    {
      "description": "The !DOCTYPE html statement at the top of HTML files. Signals the browser to use HTML5 standards mode.",
      "title": "DOCTYPE Declaration"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <html> tag enclosing the entire document. Sets the language attribute for the page.",
      "title": "HTML Root Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <head> section containing metadata and document information. Not visible on the rendered page.",
      "title": "Head Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <title> tag inside head for the browser tab text. Influences SEO and user identification.",
      "title": "Title Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <meta charset=\"UTF-8\"> tag specifying character encoding. Ensures proper text rendering across languages.",
      "title": "Meta Charset Attribute"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1\"> tag. Enables responsive design on mobile devices.",
      "title": "Meta Viewport for Mobile"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <body> section holding visible content. Contains all text, images, and interactive elements.",
      "title": "Body Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "Building blocks of HTML pages defined by tags. Consist of opening and closing tags with content in between.",
      "title": "What are HTML Elements?"
    },
    {
      "description": "Syntax for elements like <p> for opening and </p> for closing. Encloses content to apply structure.",
      "title": "Opening and Closing Tags"
    },
    {
      "description": "Elements like <img> or <br> that do not require closing tags. Used for standalone items without content.",
      "title": "Self-Closing Tags"
    },
    {
      "description": "Placing elements inside other elements for hierarchy. Maintains proper order to avoid invalid structure.",
      "title": "Nesting Elements"
    },
    {
      "description": "Elements like <div> and <p> that start on new lines and take full width. Used for major content sections.",
      "title": "Block-Level Elements"
    },
    {
      "description": "Elements like <span> and <a> that flow within text lines. Do not break the flow or add line breaks.",
      "title": "Inline Elements"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <p> tag for blocks of text. Automatically adds spacing between paragraphs.",
      "title": "Paragraph Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "Elements from <h1> to <h6> for hierarchical titles. <h1> as main heading, decreasing in importance.",
      "title": "Heading Levels"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <ul> element for bullet-point lists. Contains <li> items without specific order.",
      "title": "Unordered Lists"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <ol> element for numbered lists. Contains <li> items in sequential order.",
      "title": "Ordered Lists"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <li> tag inside ul or ol for each list entry. Renders as bullets or numbers based on parent.",
      "title": "List Item Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <div> tag as a generic container for grouping content. Often used with CSS for layout.",
      "title": "Division Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <span> tag as an inline generic container. Applies styles or scripts to parts of text.",
      "title": "Span Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "Key-value pairs added to opening tags for extra information. Provide functionality or metadata to elements.",
      "title": "What are HTML Attributes?"
    },
    {
      "description": "Format like attribute=\"value\" inside opening tags. Multiple attributes separated by spaces.",
      "title": "Attribute Syntax"
    },
    {
      "description": "Attributes like id and class applicable to most elements. Used for identification and styling.",
      "title": "Global Attributes"
    },
    {
      "description": "The id attribute for unique element identification. Ensures one id per page for targeting.",
      "title": "ID Attribute"
    },
    {
      "description": "The class attribute for grouping multiple elements. Allows reuse of styles or scripts.",
      "title": "Class Attribute"
    },
    {
      "description": "The title attribute for tooltip text on hover. Provides additional descriptive information.",
      "title": "Title Attribute"
    },
    {
      "description": "The style attribute for inline CSS rules. Applies direct styling without external files.",
      "title": "Style Attribute"
    },
    {
      "description": "The lang attribute specifying document or element language. Aids screen readers and search engines.",
      "title": "Lang Attribute"
    },
    {
      "description": "The href attribute in <a> tags for link destinations. Points to URLs or anchors within the page.",
      "title": "Href Attribute"
    },
    {
      "description": "The src attribute in <img> or <script> tags for resource paths. Loads external files like images.",
      "title": "Src Attribute"
    },
    {
      "description": "The alt attribute in <img> tags for alternative text. Describes images for accessibility.",
      "title": "Alt Attribute"
    },
    {
      "description": "Elements for user input collection using the <form> tag. Submits data to servers via methods.",
      "title": "What are HTML Forms?"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <form> tag grouping input controls. Specifies action URL and submission method.",
      "title": "Form Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The action attribute defining the submission endpoint. URL where form data is sent.",
      "title": "Action Attribute in Forms"
    },
    {
      "description": "The method attribute as GET or POST. GET appends data to URL, POST sends in body.",
      "title": "Method Attribute in Forms"
    },
    {
      "description": "The type attribute in <input> for control behavior. Includes text, password, email, and more.",
      "title": "Input Element Types"
    },
    {
      "description": "Input type=\"text\" for single-line text entry. Common for names or search terms.",
      "title": "Text Input Field"
    },
    {
      "description": "Input type=\"password\" for obscured text entry. Hides characters as users type.",
      "title": "Password Input Field"
    },
    {
      "description": "Input type=\"email\" for email addresses. Includes built-in validation for format.",
      "title": "Email Input Field"
    },
    {
      "description": "Input type=\"number\" for numeric values. Supports min, max, and step attributes.",
      "title": "Number Input Field"
    },
    {
      "description": "Input type=\"checkbox\" for multiple selections. Allows toggling on or off.",
      "title": "Checkbox Input"
    },
    {
      "description": "Input type=\"radio\" for single selection from group. Uses name attribute for mutual exclusivity.",
      "title": "Radio Button Input"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <textarea> tag for multi-line text input. Resizable and supports rows and cols attributes.",
      "title": "Textarea Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <select> tag for dropdown menus. Contains <option> elements for choices.",
      "title": "Select Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <option> tag inside select for individual choices. Includes value and selected attributes.",
      "title": "Option Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <button> tag for clickable controls. Supports type attribute for submit or reset.",
      "title": "Button Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <label> tag associating text with form controls. Improves accessibility via for attribute.",
      "title": "Label Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The name attribute identifying form fields. Sent as key in submission data.",
      "title": "Name Attribute in Forms"
    },
    {
      "description": "The value attribute setting default or submitted content. Pre-fills fields or holds checkbox values.",
      "title": "Value Attribute in Inputs"
    },
    {
      "description": "The required attribute for mandatory fields. Triggers validation on form submission.",
      "title": "Required Attribute"
    },
    {
      "description": "The placeholder attribute for hint text in inputs. Disappears when user focuses or types.",
      "title": "Placeholder Attribute"
    },
    {
      "description": "Embedding images using the <img> element. Enhances content with visual media.",
      "title": "HTML Multimedia: Images"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <img> tag with src and alt attributes. Displays images from specified paths.",
      "title": "Image Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "Width and height attributes on <img> for sizing. Specified in pixels for layout control.",
      "title": "Width and Height Attributes"
    },
    {
      "description": "Embedding sound files using the <audio> element. Supports playback controls.",
      "title": "HTML Multimedia: Audio"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <audio> tag with src for audio sources. Includes controls attribute for player interface.",
      "title": "Audio Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The controls attribute adding play, pause, and volume UI. Enables user interaction with audio.",
      "title": "Controls Attribute in Audio"
    },
    {
      "description": "The autoplay attribute starting audio on page load. Limited by browser policies.",
      "title": "Autoplay Attribute in Audio"
    },
    {
      "description": "Embedding video files using the <video> element. Supports multiple formats.",
      "title": "HTML Multimedia: Video"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <video> tag with src or source children for video files. Displays with optional controls.",
      "title": "Video Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <source> tag inside video for fallback formats. Browser selects compatible source.",
      "title": "Source Element in Video"
    },
    {
      "description": "The poster attribute showing a preview image before playback. Displays until video starts.",
      "title": "Poster Attribute in Video"
    },
    {
      "description": "Creating hyperlinks with the <a> element. Connects pages or sections.",
      "title": "HTML Links"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <a> tag with href for destinations. Text inside becomes clickable.",
      "title": "Anchor Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "Href values starting with http:// or https:// for other sites. Opens in same tab by default.",
      "title": "External Links"
    },
    {
      "description": "Href values to same-site pages or anchors. Navigates within the website.",
      "title": "Internal Links"
    },
    {
      "description": "The target=\"_blank\" attribute for new tab openings. Prevents navigation away from current page.",
      "title": "Target Attribute in Links"
    },
    {
      "description": "Content inside <a> tags as descriptive anchors. Should clearly indicate destination.",
      "title": "Link Text"
    },
    {
      "description": "Using elements that convey meaning beyond appearance. Improves accessibility and SEO.",
      "title": "What is Semantic HTML?"
    },
    {
      "description": "Semantic tags like <article> describe content role. Non-semantic like <div> are neutral containers.",
      "title": "Semantic vs Non-Semantic Elements"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <header> tag for introductory content or navigation. Often at page or section top.",
      "title": "Header Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <nav> tag grouping main navigation links. Helps identify primary site menus.",
      "title": "Navigation Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <main> tag for primary content area. Only one per page, excluding headers and footers.",
      "title": "Main Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <article> tag for self-contained content. Suitable for blog posts or news items.",
      "title": "Article Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <section> tag for thematic content groups. Often includes headings for structure.",
      "title": "Section Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <aside> tag for tangential content. Used for sidebars or pull quotes.",
      "title": "Aside Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <footer> tag for concluding content. Contains copyright or contact info.",
      "title": "Footer Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The <figure> tag for media with <figcaption> for captions. Groups images with descriptions.",
      "title": "Figure and Figcaption"
    },
    {
      "description": "Designing HTML for users with disabilities using standards like WCAG. Ensures inclusive web experiences.",
      "title": "What is Web Accessibility?"
    },
    {
      "description": "Using proper headings and elements to create navigable outlines. Allows logical content traversal.",
      "title": "Semantic Structure for Screen Readers"
    },
    {
      "description": "Descriptive alt attributes conveying image purpose. Read by screen readers for blind users.",
      "title": "Alt Text for Images"
    },
    {
      "description": "Associating <label> with inputs using for attribute. Enables keyboard and screen reader navigation.",
      "title": "Accessible Form Labels"
    },
    {
      "description": "Ensuring focusable elements like links and buttons work with tab key. Maintains visible focus indicators.",
      "title": "Keyboard Navigation Support"
    },
    {
      "description": "Choosing text and background colors meeting contrast ratios. Improves readability for low vision users.",
      "title": "Color Contrast in HTML"
    },
    {
      "description": "The role attribute defining element purpose for assistive tech. Used when semantics are insufficient.",
      "title": "Aria Role Attribute"
    },
    {
      "description": "The aria-labelledby referencing elements for labels. Associates descriptions dynamically.",
      "title": "Aria Labelledby Attribute"
    },
    {
      "description": "The aria-describedby pointing to detailed explanations. Provides additional context for complex items.",
      "title": "Aria Describedby Attribute"
    },
    {
      "description": "Specifying language changes with lang attribute. Helps screen readers use correct pronunciation.",
      "title": "Lang Attribute for Accessibility"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "Interacción electrostática entre cationes y aniones formados por transferencia de electrones. Resulta en compuestos con altas temperaturas de fusión.",
      "title": "Definición de enlace iónico"
    },
    {
      "description": "Pérdida de electrones por átomos metálicos para lograr configuración electrónica estable. Ejemplo: sodio pierde un electrón para formar Na⁺.",
      "title": "Formación de cationes"
    },
    {
      "description": "Ganancia de electrones por átomos no metálicos para completar su octeto. Ejemplo: cloro gana un electrón para formar Cl⁻.",
      "title": "Formación de aniones"
    },
    {
      "description": "Estructura cristalina en redes tridimensionales con puntos de fusión y ebullición elevados. Conducen electricidad en estado fundido o disuelto.",
      "title": "Propiedades de compuestos iónicos"
    },
    {
      "description": "Compartición de pares de electrones entre átomos no metálicos para alcanzar estabilidad electrónica. Forma moléculas discretas.",
      "title": "Definición de enlace covalente"
    },
    {
      "description": "Compartición de un par de electrones entre dos átomos. Ejemplo: enlace en H₂ donde cada hidrógeno aporta un electrón.",
      "title": "Enlace covalente simple"
    },
    {
      "description": "Compartición de dos pares de electrones entre átomos. Ejemplo: enlace en O₂ con cuatro electrones compartidos.",
      "title": "Enlace covalente doble"
    },
    {
      "description": "Compartición de tres pares de electrones entre átomos. Ejemplo: enlace en N₂ con seis electrones compartidos.",
      "title": "Enlace covalente triple"
    },
    {
      "description": "Bajos puntos de fusión y ebullición en comparación con iónicos. Generalmente no conducen electricidad.",
      "title": "Propiedades de compuestos covalentes"
    },
    {
      "description": "Atracción entre cationes metálicos y electrones deslocalizados en una 'nube' electrónica. Explica la maleabilidad y conductividad de metales.",
      "title": "Definición de enlace metálico"
    },
    {
      "description": "Electrones de valencia libres que se mueven entre cationes metálicos. Permite la conductividad eléctrica y térmica.",
      "title": "Nube de electrones deslocalizados"
    },
    {
      "description": "Alta ductilidad, maleabilidad y brillo debido a la deformación de la red sin romper enlaces. Ejemplos: hierro y cobre.",
      "title": "Propiedades de sólidos metálicos"
    },
    {
      "description": "Teoría que predice geometrías moleculares basadas en repulsión de pares de electrones alrededor del átomo central. Asume forma que minimiza repulsiones.",
      "title": "Teoría VSEPR básica"
    },
    {
      "description": "Estructura con dos dominios de electrones y ángulo de 180°. Ejemplo: molécula de CO₂.",
      "title": "Geometría lineal"
    },
    {
      "description": "Estructura con tres dominios de electrones y ángulos de 120°. Ejemplo: molécula de BF₃.",
      "title": "Geometría trigonal plana"
    },
    {
      "description": "Estructura con cuatro dominios de electrones y ángulos de 109.5°. Ejemplo: molécula de CH₄.",
      "title": "Geometría tetraédrica"
    },
    {
      "description": "Estructura con cinco dominios de electrones: tres ecuatoriales a 120° y dos axiales a 90°. Ejemplo: molécula de PCl₅.",
      "title": "Geometría bipiramidal trigonal"
    },
    {
      "description": "Estructura con seis dominios de electrones y ángulos de 90°. Ejemplo: molécula de SF₆.",
      "title": "Geometría octaédrica"
    },
    {
      "description": "Pares de electrones no enlazantes ocupan más espacio y distorsionan geometrías. Ejemplo: en NH₃, un par solitario reduce ángulos a 107°.",
      "title": "Efecto de pares solitarios en VSEPR"
    },
    {
      "description": "Explica enlaces covalentes mediante solapamiento de orbitales atómicos. Predice hibridación para coincidir con geometrías observadas.",
      "title": "Definición de teoría del enlace de valencia"
    },
    {
      "description": "Mezcla de un orbital s y un p para formar dos orbitales híbridos lineales. Usada en moléculas como BeCl₂.",
      "title": "Hibridación sp"
    },
    {
      "description": "Mezcla de un s y dos p para tres orbitales en plano trigonal. Ejemplo: en moléculas como BF₃.",
      "title": "Hibridación sp²"
    },
    {
      "description": "Mezcla de un s y tres p para cuatro orbitales tetraédricos. Ejemplo: en moléculas como CH₄.",
      "title": "Hibridación sp³"
    },
    {
      "description": "Mezcla de un s, tres p y un d para cinco orbitales bipiramidales trigonal. Ejemplo: en PCl₅.",
      "title": "Hibridación sp³d"
    },
    {
      "description": "Mezcla de un s, tres p y dos d para seis orbitales octaédricos. Ejemplo: en SF₆.",
      "title": "Hibridación sp³d²"
    },
    {
      "description": "Enlace formado por solapamiento frontal de orbitales a lo largo del eje internuclear. Presente en todos los enlaces simples.",
      "title": "Solapamiento sigma"
    },
    {
      "description": "Enlace formado por solapamiento lateral de orbitales p. Ocurre en enlaces dobles y triples además del sigma.",
      "title": "Solapamiento pi"
    },
    {
      "description": "Orbitales formados por combinación lineal de orbitales atómicos. Describen electrones en moléculas como enlaces o antienlaces.",
      "title": "Definición de orbitales moleculares"
    },
    {
      "description": "Orbital con menor energía que los atómicos, donde electrones estabilizan la molécula. Formado por solapamiento constructivo.",
      "title": "Orbital molecular de enlace"
    },
    {
      "description": "Orbital con mayor energía que los atómicos, donde electrones desestabilizan la molécula. Formado por solapamiento destructivo.",
      "title": "Orbital molecular antienlace"
    },
    {
      "description": "Medida de fuerza del enlace: (número de electrones en enlazantes - antienlazantes)/2. Ejemplo: en H₂ es 1.",
      "title": "Orden de enlace en orbitales moleculares"
    },
    {
      "description": "Combinación de 1s atómicos forma σ y σ* con dos electrones en σ. Predice enlace simple estable.",
      "title": "Diagrama de orbitales moleculares para H₂"
    },
    {
      "description": "Incluye orbitales σ y π de valencia con electrones no apareados. Explica paramagnetismo de O₂.",
      "title": "Diagrama de orbitales moleculares para O₂"
    },
    {
      "description": "Desigualdad en la compartición de electrones debido a diferencias en electronegatividad. Crea dipolos parciales en enlaces covalentes.",
      "title": "Definición de polaridad en enlaces"
    },
    {
      "description": "Medida de la capacidad de un átomo para atraer electrones en un enlace. Escala de Pauling: F es 4.0, más electronegativo.",
      "title": "Electronegatividad de elementos"
    },
    {
      "description": "Enlace con diferencia de electronegatividad entre 0.4 y 1.7. Ejemplo: en HCl, cloro atrae más electrones.",
      "title": "Enlace covalente polar"
    },
    {
      "description": "Enlace con diferencia de electronegatividad menor a 0.4. Ejemplo: en Cl₂, compartición igual.",
      "title": "Enlace covalente no polar"
    },
    {
      "description": "Producto de la carga parcial y la distancia en un dipolo. Determina polaridad molecular global.",
      "title": "Momento dipolar en moléculas"
    },
    {
      "description": "Moléculas con momento dipolar neto no cero son polares; simétricas como CO₂ son no polares. Afecta solubilidad y fuerzas intermoleculares.",
      "title": "Moléculas polares vs. no polares"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "The ordinary least squares estimator projects the dependent variable vector onto the column space of the design matrix X.",
      "title": "OLS as Projection onto Column Space"
    },
    {
      "description": "Fitted values are the orthogonal projection of y onto the span of X, minimizing squared residuals.",
      "title": "Fitted Values in OLS"
    },
    {
      "description": "Residuals are the component of y orthogonal to the column space of X, perpendicular to fitted values.",
      "title": "Residuals in OLS"
    },
    {
      "description": "The OLS coefficient vector beta-hat equals (X'X)^{-1} X' y, derived from projection properties.",
      "title": "OLS Estimator Formula"
    },
    {
      "description": "The sum of squared residuals measures the unexplained variation in y after projection onto X.",
      "title": "Sum of Squared Residuals"
    },
    {
      "description": "Total sum of squares equals explained sum of squares plus residual sum of squares in OLS geometry.",
      "title": "Total Sum of Squares Decomposition"
    },
    {
      "description": "The model assumes E[y | X] = X beta, linear in parameters but possibly nonlinear in variables.",
      "title": "Linearity in Parameters Assumption"
    },
    {
      "description": "Errors satisfy E[epsilon | X] = 0, meaning regressors are uncorrelated with all error terms.",
      "title": "Strict Exogeneity Assumption"
    },
    {
      "description": "Columns of X are linearly independent, ensuring the design matrix has full column rank.",
      "title": "No Perfect Collinearity Assumption"
    },
    {
      "description": "Variance of errors is constant: Var(epsilon_i | X) = sigma^2 for all i.",
      "title": "Homoskedasticity Assumption"
    },
    {
      "description": "Errors have zero mean, constant variance, and zero covariance: Var(epsilon | X) = sigma^2 I.",
      "title": "Spherically Distributed Errors"
    },
    {
      "description": "Parameters are identified if the matrix X'X has full rank equal to the number of parameters.",
      "title": "Identification via Rank Condition"
    },
    {
      "description": "The number of excluded exogenous variables must be at least as many as the number of endogenous regressors.",
      "title": "Order Condition for Identification"
    },
    {
      "description": "Identification ensures a unique beta that satisfies the population moment conditions.",
      "title": "Unique Solution in Identified Models"
    },
    {
      "description": "Under classical assumptions, OLS estimators are BLUE: best linear unbiased estimators.",
      "title": "Gauss-Markov Theorem Statement"
    },
    {
      "description": "E[beta-hat] = beta under linearity, exogeneity, and no perfect collinearity.",
      "title": "Unbiasedness of OLS"
    },
    {
      "description": "beta-hat is a linear function of the dependent variable y.",
      "title": "Linearity of OLS Estimators"
    },
    {
      "description": "Var(beta-hat) = sigma^2 (X'X)^{-1} under homoskedasticity and spherical errors.",
      "title": "Variance-Covariance Matrix of OLS"
    },
    {
      "description": "OLS has the smallest variance among all linear unbiased estimators of beta.",
      "title": "Efficiency in Gauss-Markov"
    },
    {
      "description": "The t-statistic tests H0: beta_j = 0 using beta-hat_j divided by its standard error.",
      "title": "t-Statistic for Single Coefficient"
    },
    {
      "description": "The F-statistic tests multiple linear restrictions on beta using explained over residual variance.",
      "title": "F-Statistic for Joint Hypothesis"
    },
    {
      "description": "Under H0 and assumptions, the t-statistic follows a t-distribution with n - k degrees of freedom.",
      "title": "Distribution of t-Statistic"
    },
    {
      "description": "Under H0, the F-statistic follows an F-distribution with q and n - k degrees of freedom.",
      "title": "Distribution of F-Statistic"
    },
    {
      "description": "RSS measures model fit; smaller RSS indicates better explanation of variation in y.",
      "title": "Residual Sum of Squares in Diagnostics"
    },
    {
      "description": "R^2 equals 1 minus RSS over total sum of squares, measuring proportion of variance explained.",
      "title": "R-Squared Statistic"
    },
    {
      "description": "Adjusted R^2 penalizes for additional regressors: 1 - (RSS/(n-k)) / (TSS/(n-1)).",
      "title": "Adjusted R-Squared"
    },
    {
      "description": "Breusch-Pagan test regresses squared residuals on X and tests significance of those coefficients.",
      "title": "Detecting Heteroskedasticity with Breusch-Pagan"
